# Exploratory Analysis

First, let's plot the empirical data and take a look at what we see.

## Main Effects

### Children vs Adults

If we ignore condition, do adults and children respond similarly?

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false
emotion_shape %>%
  group_by(group) %>%
  summarize(
    prop_emotion = mean(emotion_response),
    se = sqrt(prop_emotion * (1 - prop_emotion) / n()),
    n = n()
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = group, y = prop_emotion, fill = group)) +
  geom_col(width = 0.6, alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = prop_emotion - se, ymax = prop_emotion + se),
                width = 0.2) +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(prop_emotion, 2)), vjust = -2) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,1)) +
  labs(y = "Proportion of emotion response = 1", x = "Group") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")
```

Yes, adults and children respond similarly when we ignore condition.

### Base vs Complement

If we ignore group, do we see similar responses for each condition?

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false
emotion_shape %>%
  group_by(condition) %>%
  summarize(
    prop_emotion = mean(emotion_response),
    se = sqrt(prop_emotion * (1 - prop_emotion) / n()),
    n = n()
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = condition, y = prop_emotion, fill = condition)) +
  geom_col(width = 0.6, alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = prop_emotion - se, ymax = prop_emotion + se),
                width = 0.2) +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(prop_emotion, 2)), vjust = -2) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,1)) +
  labs(y = "Proportion of emotion response = 1", x = "Condition") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")
```

Participants respond differently to the base vs complement conditions.

## Interaction effects

This graph answers the question: Do adults and children respond similarly to each condition? We already know that if we ignore group, there is a difference, but let's what each group looks like.

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false
emotion_shape %>%
  group_by(condition,group) %>%
  summarize(prop_emotion = mean(emotion_response),
            se = sqrt(prop_emotion * (1 - prop_emotion) / n()),
            n = n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = condition, y = prop_emotion, fill = condition)) +
  facet_wrap(~group) +
  geom_col(width = 0.6, alpha = 0.8) +  
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = prop_emotion - se, ymax = prop_emotion + se),
                width = 0.2) +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(prop_emotion, 2)), vjust = -2.5) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,1)) +
  labs(y = "Proportion of emotion response = 1", x = "condition") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")
```

It doesn't seem like one group is driving the main effect we saw.

Now let's look at the same data, but now focusing on the question: Do adults and children respond similarly to each other for each condition?

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false
emotion_shape %>%
  group_by(condition,group) %>%
  summarize(prop_emotion = mean(emotion_response),
            se = sqrt(prop_emotion * (1 - prop_emotion) / n()),
            n = n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = group, y = prop_emotion, fill = group)) +
  facet_wrap(~condition) +
  geom_col(width = 0.6, alpha = 0.8) +  
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = prop_emotion - se, ymax = prop_emotion + se),
                width = 0.2) +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(prop_emotion, 2)), vjust = -2.5) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,1)) +
  labs(y = "Proportion of emotion response = 1", x = "group") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")
```

We see that for the base condition, adults and children respond very similarly. For the complement condition, adults and children differ a little bit, but it doesn't seem to be a very large or meaningful difference.

# Bayesian Data Analysis

Now let's model the data.

## The basics

I used a logistic Bayesian regression with the following formula:

```
emotion_response ~ 0 + Intercept + group * condition + 
  (1 | participant_id) +
  (1 | test_trial)
```

The Intercept represents the probability of an emotion response from *adult* in *base* condition.

Here's the model output with a forest plot of the effects. Below it is an easier-to-read table. For the forest plot, the dot represents the median estimate, the thick black lines and skinny black lines represent 66% and 95% highest density credible intervals.

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false
summary(m_shape)
```

```{r}
